arwickshire, England":"Ullenhall, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Ashburnham, Sussex, England":"Ashburnham, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hammond","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Ha(i)mon</i>, the oblique case form of the ancient Germanic <i>Ha(i)mo</i>, a short form of various compound names beginning with <i>haim</i> ‘home’. It frequently developed excrescent <i>-d</i>, giving <i>Hamond</i>, <i>Haimund</i>, and <i>Hawmond</i>. Alternatively, the name could derive from the Middle English personal name <i>Hamund</i> (Old Norse <i>Hámundr</i>, composed of the elements <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’), which may have been used in Normandy and in 12th-century eastern England, but the former explanation is more likely. The surname was sometimes confused with   Almond   and   Ammon  .","English: in the Bradford area of Yorkshire, the name is a shortened form of <b>Ormondroyd</b>, formerly <i>Hamondesrode</i>, from a lost place in Birstall (Yorkshire), named with the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Hamon</i> (1 above) + Middle English <i>roid</i>, a southern Yorkshire pronunciation of Old English <i>rod</i> ‘clearing’.","Irish: generally an importation from England, but occasionally an adopted name for <b>Mac Ámoinn</b>, see   McCammon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hammonds","meanings":["English (Shropshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Hammond  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Almond","meanings":["Hebrew: Hidden"]},{"name":"Hammett","meanings":["English (southwestern England, especialy Devon): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hamet</i>, a pet form of ancient Germanic <i>Hamo</i> (see   Hammond   1)."]},{"name":"Hamon","meanings":["Pronounced ‘<b>ay</b>-mon’ Anglicized spelling of Irish <i>Éamon(n)</i> or <i>Éaman(n)</i>, Irish forms of   Edmund .  Although it still has an essentially Irish flavour, the name was popularized throughout Britain in the 1950s due to the fame of the broadcaster  Eamon Andrews  (  1922–87 )."]},{"name":"Hamlin","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, from the Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Hamelin</i>, a double diminutive of <i>Hamo</i> (see   Hammond  ).","French: variant of   Hamelin   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","Americanized form of Finnish <b>Hämäläinen</b> (see   Hamalainen  )."]},{"name":"Hampson","meanings":["The Greek form of the Scripture name, which Simonis translates, 'sol eximius,' i.e. illustrious sun; the Rev. A. Jones 'splendid sun,' i.e. great joy and felicity; Tregelles, ' solar, like the sun; ' and Fuerstius, ' sonnenahnlicher ' that is, one who resembles the sun (from shemesh, the sun)."]},{"name":"Haimes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Yacov, Yosef.","English: variant, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, of <b>Haime</b>, of Norman origin, from the Old French personal name <i>Haim</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Haimo</i>, from <i>haim-</i> ‘home’), often Latinized as <i>Hamo</i>. Compare   Hammond  .","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname."]},{"name":"Hammon","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Ken): variant of   Hammond  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hammond Ashburnham was born in 1240, in Bromham, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Ashburnham, was 11237 and his mother, Catherine PEVEREL, was 30. He married Maud de Elton in 1220, in Bromham, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters."},"et":{"1240–":"1240–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1264–Female":"1264–Surnud","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1267–Male":"1267–Surnud","1270–1300":"1270–1300","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1267